{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507110"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2603"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2603"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.25,0.34,0.04,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53998"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39469"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1236"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3995"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53998"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a new lesion on her vulva that she noticed when showering today. She denies any pain or discharge from the lesion. She has multiple sexual partners and uses barrier contraception inconsistently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Genital examination shows a firm ulcer on her vulva that has a smooth base, and bilateral inguinal lymphadenopathy is present. Rapid plasma reagin and \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E particle agglutination tests are positive. She is treated with the appropriate antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEight hours later, she presents to the Emergency Department complaining of generalised muscle aches and a headache. On examination, she appears unwell and is shivering. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 106/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. She states that the vulval lesion has become larger and redder than this morning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start oral prednisolone","Continue intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin weekly for three weeks","Provide supportive care with antipyretics","Administer oral antihistamines","Administer intravenous ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing a Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction (JHR), which is a self-limiting reaction that occurs in about a third of patients receiving treatment for syphilis and other spirochetal infections. Symptoms typically develop within 6-12 hours, though can be seen up to 24 hours after administration of antibiotics. It is characterised by fever, headache, myalgia, and often a worsening of skin lesions. JHR is not an allergic response to penicillin, but rather a result of rapid killing of spirochetes and subsequent release of inflammatory mediators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive care with antipyretics\u003C/strong\u003E. Patients may initially develop hypertension and hyperventilation, however in the later stages of the reaction vasodilation occurs and hypotension may also require treatment with intravenous fluids. In some situations, the reaction can be severe, resulting in acute kidney injury, liver dysfunction, pulmonary oedema or haemorrhage and meningitis. For patients who are pregnant and develop JHR, there is a risk of preterm labour and fetal distress. Fetuses that have congenital syphilis are more likely to be affected, and in severe cases fetal death can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin weekly for three weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. This is the recommended treatment for late latent syphilis, however this patient presents with primary syphilis so a single dose is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting oral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for managing JHR following treatment of primary or secondary syphilis. While corticosteroids might theoretically reduce the inflammatory response, there is insufficient evidence to support their use in this context. For patients with cardiovascular or neurosyphilis, oral prednisolone may be administered with the doses of benzathine benzylpenicillin to reduce the chance of developing JHR. This is because if a reaction occurs, it can be more severe; however, the evidence for this is still limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering oral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E will have no effect on this patient as JHR is not an allergy-mediated response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated. The patient has already received appropriate treatment for syphilis with benzathine benzylpenicillin, which remains the first-line treatment and she does not require any further antibiotics at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction is more common in patients with early syphilis, particularly primary and secondary stages. Patients should be informed about the possibility of this reaction when treatment is initiated. The reaction is usually self-limiting and resolves within 24-48 hours. Management focuses on symptomatic relief with antipyretics, adequate hydration, and reassurance. Close monitoring is advisable, especially in pregnant women or patients with cardiovascular disease, as the reaction can occasionally be severe.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction is a self-limiting reaction that can occur within 24 hours of treatment for syphilis, characterised by fever, headache, myalgia, and worsening of skin lesions.","Management of the Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction is primarily supportive, including antipyretics and reassurance."],"references":["Syphilis [published 2019 Apr]. In: eTG complete [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au\u003E","Australian STI Management Guidelines. http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis. Accessed 13th of June, 2021.","Butler T. The Jarisch-Herxheimer Reaction After Antibiotic Treatment of Spirochetal Infections: A Review of Recent Cases and Our Understanding of Pathogenesis. Am J Trop Med Hyg. 2017 Jan 11;96(1):46-52. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5239707/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39469"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2603"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":